cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.NE, cs.CR 

The paper focuses on the use of Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) for computer vision-based physics problems, specifically event vertex finding and hadron multiplicity classification in the MINERvA experiment at Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also discusses the relationship between a CNN's architecture and its performance, which falls under the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The use of a model selection algorithm called Multi-node Evolutionary Neural Networks for Deep Learning (MENNDL) also suggests the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper discusses the use of machine learning models to predict network performance, which falls under the sub-category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security).
